"" ><div class="comment-meta clear"><span class="comment-author"><strong><span class="author"><a id="author_t1_1v3q" href="http://lesswrong.com/user/Psychohistorian/">Psychohistorian</a></span></strong></span><span class="comment-date">08 April 2010 03:51:24PM</span><span class="votes " id='score_t1_1v3q'>0 points</span><script type="text/javascript">vl['t1_1v3q'] = ['-1 points', '0 points', '1 point' ];</script>&#32;<a href="#" class="expand" onclick="return hidecomment('t1_1v3q')">[-]</a></div><div id="body_t1_1v3q" class="comment-content"><div class="md"><p>This is just playing with connotations. A bachelor is an unmarried man, so one could say that Tom acts like a bachelor despite being married. He is not a bachelor, though. To show this has a practical implication, assume Tom met Mary: the two could not get married immediately. If he were a bachelor, they could. He therefore lacks necessary properties of bachelorness (most significantly, not being married), and cannot be a bachelor, even if he may live his life much as a bachelor would.</p></div></div><div style="display: none;" id="edit_body_t1_1v3q"></div><div class="comment-links"><ul class="clear"><li class="first"><a id="up_t1_1v3q" class="up" onclick="showcover(true, 'vote_t1_1v3q')" >Vote up</a></li><li><a id="down_t1_1v3q" class="down" onclick="showcover(true, 'vote_t1_1v3q')" >Vote down</a></li><li><a id="permalink_t1_1v3q" href="http://lesswrong.com/lw/20y/rationality_quotes_april_2010/1v3q?c=1" class=" " target="_parent" >Permalink</a></li><li><a id="parent_t1_1v3q" href="#1ux6" class="bylink">Parent</a></li><li><a id="reply_a_t1_1v3q" class="" href="javascript:reply('t1_1v3q')">Reply</a></li></ul><span id=status_t1_1v3q class="error" style="display: none;"></span></div></div></div><div id="child_t1_1v3q" class="child" ></div><div class="clearleft"><!--IE6sux--></div></div><div class="clearleft"><!--IE6sux--></div></div></div><div class="clearleft"><!--IE6sux--></div></div><div class="clearleft"><!--